[49m[38;5;10m+      1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 8.5: Problem List Extraction
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Medium · **Phase:** Integration · **Estimated Cost:** ~$0.002-0.01 per note
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Every patient in your EHR has a problem list. In theory, it's the authoritative summary of active diagnoses and conditions: the single place a clinician can glance to understand what's going on with this patient. In practice, problem lists are one of the most poorly maintained data assets in healthcare.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's what actually happens. A patient with diabetes, hypertension, chronic kidney disease, depression, and a resolved pneumonia from last year shows up for an annual visit. The problem list in the EHR might say "HTN" (added by the PCP three years ago), "Type 2 DM" (added during a hospitalization), and nothing else. The CKD was diagnosed six months ago but the nephrologist documented it in a consult note and never updated the problem list. The depression is mentioned in every progress note but nobody added it formally. The pneumonia is still listed as active because nobody marked it resolved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is not a rare scenario. Studies consistently show that EHR problem lists are incomplete, with sensitivity for known diagnoses ranging from 40-70% depending on the condition and setting. Chronic conditions are under-represented. Resolved conditions linger. New diagnoses get documented in notes but never propagated to the structured list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The downstream impact is real. Clinical decision support fires (or doesn't fire) based on the problem list. Quality measures get reported against it. Risk adjustment coding depends on it. Care coordination tools use it to identify patients who need outreach. When the problem list is wrong, all of those downstream systems produce wrong results, silently.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The information exists. It's in progress notes, discharge summaries, consult notes, procedure notes. Clinicians document diagnoses in narrative text all the time. The gap is extracting those mentions, determining which represent active problems versus historical or resolved ones, and reconciling them against the existing problem list. That extraction and classification problem is what we're solving here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Technology: Clinical Concept Extraction and Assertion Detection
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### What Is Problem List Extraction?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Problem list extraction is a two-stage NLP task. First, you identify mentions of clinical problems (diagnoses, conditions, symptoms) in unstructured text. Second, you classify each mention by its assertion status: is this problem currently active, historically relevant but resolved, negated ("no evidence of diabetes"), related to family history, or hypothetical ("if she develops CKD")?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first stage is a variant of Named Entity Recognition (NER) focused on clinical conditions. The second stage is assertion classification, sometimes called contextual analysis or negation/temporality detection. Both stages must work together: extracting "diabetes" from a note is useless without knowing whether the patient has diabetes, used to have diabetes, doesn't have diabetes, or has a family history of diabetes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Named Entity Recognition for Clinical Problems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Clinical NER for problems targets a broad category. Unlike medication extraction (where you're looking for drug names with well-defined lexical patterns), problem mentions come in many forms:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Formal diagnoses**: "Type 2 diabetes mellitus," "chronic obstructive pulmonary disease," "major depressive disorder"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Abbreviations and acronyms**: "HTN," "CHF," "COPD," "DM2," "CKD Stage 3b," "OA," "BPH"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Descriptive mentions**: "elevated blood pressure," "worsening kidney function," "feeling down and hopeless"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eponyms and named conditions**: "Hashimoto's thyroiditis," "Parkinson's disease," "Crohn's"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Symptom clusters that imply a condition**: "polyuria, polydipsia, and unexplained weight loss" (implying undiagnosed diabetes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The challenge is that problem mentions don't follow a single lexical pattern. Drug names are at least constrained to a finite (if large) vocabulary. Clinical problems span the entire breadth of medicine, from "headache" to "anti-NMDA receptor encephalitis." A good extraction system needs both dictionary coverage and contextual pattern recognition.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Modern approaches use transformer-based models trained on annotated clinical corpora. The i2b2 2010 challenge established benchmarks for clinical concept extraction, and subsequent datasets (ShARe/CLEF, n2c2) have pushed the field forward. Current state-of-the-art models achieve F1 scores in the 85-92% range for clinical problem extraction, depending on the dataset and entity granularity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Assertion Classification: The Hard Part
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Extracting a problem mention is step one. Determining what that mention means in context is step two, and it's significantly harder.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Consider these sentences, all from the same progress note:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - "Patient has well-controlled type 2 diabetes." (Active, present)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - "History of pneumonia in 2022, resolved." (Historical, resolved)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - "No evidence of malignancy on imaging." (Negated)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - "Mother and sister both have breast cancer." (Family history)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - "If renal function continues to decline, may need dialysis." (Hypothetical)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     58[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - "Rule out pulmonary embolism." (Uncertain/possible)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     59[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     60[0m:[38;5;10m[49m All six contain clinical problem mentions. Only the first represents something that belongs on the active problem list. The assertion classifier must distinguish these contexts reliably, because putting a negated condition on the active problem list is worse than not extracting it at all.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     61[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     62[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Assertion classification approaches:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     63[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     64[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Rule-based (NegEx, ConText)**: The classic approach. NegEx (2001) uses trigger terms and scope rules to detect negation ("no," "denies," "without," "absent"). ConText extends this to temporality ("history of," "previously") and experiencer ("family history," "mother has"). Simple, fast, interpretable. Still competitive for straightforward patterns. Falls apart on complex sentence structures or implicit negation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     65[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     66[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Statistical/ML models**: CRF or SVM classifiers trained on assertion-annotated corpora. Features include surrounding tokens, dependency parse features, section headers, and trigger term presence. Better than pure rules at handling ambiguous cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     67[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     68[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Transformer-based models**: Fine-tuned BERT variants that jointly model extraction and assertion. These encode enough context to handle sentences like "She was evaluated for PE but CT was negative" (where "PE" is negated, but the negation signal is several tokens away and syntactically complex). Current best performers.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     69[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     70[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Managed NLP services**: Cloud services that return assertion traits (NEGATION, PAST_HISTORY, HYPOTHETICAL, FAMILY_HISTORY) alongside extracted entities. These package trained models behind APIs and handle both extraction and assertion in a single call.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     71[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     72[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Negation Detection: Deserves Its Own Discussion
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     73[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     74[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Negation is the single most important assertion type to get right, because a false positive (treating a negated condition as present) directly corrupts the problem list. It's also more nuanced than it appears.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     75[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     76[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Simple negation: "No diabetes." "Denies chest pain." "Without evidence of CHF." These are handled well by rule-based systems and any trained model.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     77[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     78[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Distant negation: "The CT scan performed last Thursday to evaluate the patient's persistent cough showed no evidence of malignancy in the right lung." The negation trigger ("no evidence") is 20+ tokens from "malignancy." Scope-based rules struggle here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     79[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     80[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Implicit negation: "Blood glucose has been normal on all recent labs." This implies the patient does not have diabetes, but the word "no" or "denies" never appears. Pure trigger-based systems miss this entirely.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     81[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     82[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Double negation: "Not without risk of cardiac complications." This is technically affirming risk, but pattern matchers that see "not" and "without" might over-negate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     83[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     84[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Negation of negation: "Her previous denial of chest pain is inconsistent with the current presentation." The assertion status here is complex and arguably ambiguous.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     85[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In practice, you'll get 90-95% of negation right with a good model. The remaining 5-10% is where clinical NLP earns its reputation for difficulty.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     88[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Terminology Normalization: SNOMED CT and ICD-10
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     89[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     90[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Once you've extracted a problem and determined it's active, you need to map it to a standard code. Two coding systems dominate:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     91[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     92[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **SNOMED CT** (Systematized Nomenclature of Medicine, Clinical Terms): The rich ontological standard. SNOMED has over 350,000 concepts organized in a hierarchy with relationships (is-a, finding-site, associated-morphology). It's the preferred terminology for clinical documentation and problem lists because of its granularity and expressiveness.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     93[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **ICD-10-CM** (International Classification of Diseases, 10th Revision, Clinical Modification): The billing and reporting standard. About 70,000 codes. Required for claims and quality reporting. Less granular than SNOMED for clinical documentation but universally understood by administrative systems.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     96[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In practice, you often need both: SNOMED for the problem list (because it captures clinical nuance) and ICD-10 for downstream billing and quality workflows. SNOMED-to-ICD-10 maps exist (maintained by NLM and SNOMED International) but are not one-to-one; many SNOMED concepts map to multiple ICD-10 codes depending on context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     97[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     98[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The normalization challenge mirrors what we saw with RxNorm in Recipe 8.4: the same condition can be expressed dozens of ways in text, and all of those need to resolve to the same concept code. "CHF," "congestive heart failure," "heart failure with reduced ejection fraction," "systolic heart failure," and "HFrEF" all need to land in the right neighborhood of SNOMED/ICD-10, at the appropriate level of specificity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     99[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    100[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### The General Architecture Pattern
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    101[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    102[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    103[0m:[38;5;10m[49m [Clinical Note] → [Section Detection] → [Problem NER] → [Assertion Classification] → [Terminology Normalization] → [Problem List Reconciliation] → [Structured Output]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    104[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Section Detection**: Identify note sections to provide context. Problem mentions in "Assessment/Plan" are highly likely to be active. Mentions in "Family History" should be tagged as such. Mentions in "Past Medical History" might be either active or resolved depending on additional context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Problem NER**: Extract spans of text that represent clinical problems, conditions, diagnoses, or symptoms. Tag each with begin/end offsets and a confidence score.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Assertion Classification**: For each extracted problem, determine its assertion status: present, absent (negated), possible, conditional, historical, family history, or hypothetical. This is the gate that prevents negated and historical conditions from polluting the active problem list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Terminology Normalization**: Map the extracted text to SNOMED CT and/or ICD-10-CM codes. Handle abbreviations, synonyms, and varying levels of specificity. Return ranked candidates with confidence scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Problem List Reconciliation**: Compare extracted active problems against the existing problem list. Identify: (a) problems documented in notes but missing from the list, (b) problems on the list that notes suggest are resolved, (c) problems that might need specificity updates (e.g., "diabetes" on the list but notes consistently say "type 2 diabetes with nephropathy").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Structured Output**: Produce a machine-readable representation with the problem text, SNOMED code, ICD-10 code, assertion status, source note reference, and confidence scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Comprehend Medical for clinical NER and assertion detection.** Comprehend Medical's `DetectEntitiesV2` API extracts medical conditions (category: MEDICAL_CONDITION) with associated traits including NEGATION, SYMPTOM, SIGN, and DIAGNOSIS differentiation. It also returns assertion traits (NEGATION, HYPOTHETICAL) and attributes like ACUITY (chronic vs. acute). For condition-to-code mapping, the `InferICD10CM` and `InferSNOMEDCT` APIs take clinical text and return ranked terminology codes with confidence scores. Together, these three APIs handle extraction, assertion, and normalization as managed services.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for note storage and results.** Clinical notes arrive from HL7 feeds, EHR exports, or ADT messages. S3 provides encrypted staging for incoming notes, archival for extraction results, and a trigger mechanism (S3 event notifications) for automated processing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for extraction orchestration.** Each note goes through a stateless pipeline: receive text, detect sections, call Comprehend Medical APIs, assemble structured output. Lambda's request-based scaling handles both real-time single-note processing and burst loads during batch operations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for problem list storage.** Extracted problems need fast lookups by patient ID (for reconciliation views) and by problem code (for population-level queries). DynamoDB supports both with a composite key design: patient ID as partition key, problem code as sort key.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Step Functions for batch reconciliation.** When running extraction against a historical note corpus to identify problem list gaps across a patient panel, Step Functions coordinates the parallel processing, handles retries on throttling, and tracks completion status.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart LR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Clinical Note Source\nHL7/EHR/ADT] -->|Store| B[S3 Bucket\nnotes-inbox/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|S3 Event| C[Lambda\nproblem-extractor]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|DetectEntitiesV2| D[Comprehend Medical]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Entities + Traits| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|InferICD10CM| E[Comprehend Medical\nICD-10]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|InferSNOMEDCT| F[Comprehend Medical\nSNOMED CT]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E -->|ICD-10 Codes| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     F -->|SNOMED Codes| C
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Reconcile| G[DynamoDB\npatient-problems]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Full Results| H[S3\nresults/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style B fill:#f9f,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style E fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style F fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style G fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Comprehend Medical, Amazon S3, AWS Lambda, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Step Functions (for batch) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `comprehendmedical:DetectEntitiesV2`, `comprehendmedical:InferICD10CM`, `comprehendmedical:InferSNOMEDCT`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `dynamodb:UpdateItem` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed (required: clinical notes contain PHI) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | S3: SSE-KMS; DynamoDB: encryption at rest (default); Lambda CloudWatch log groups: KMS encryption (logs may contain extracted clinical data); all API calls over TLS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Lambda in VPC with VPC endpoints for S3, Comprehend Medical, DynamoDB, and CloudWatch Logs |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled: log all Comprehend Medical and S3 API calls for HIPAA audit trail |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic clinical notes with problem mentions across sections. MIMIC-III (with DUA) provides realistic note structures. n2c2 datasets offer annotated clinical text for validation. Never use real patient notes in dev without proper IRB/DUA. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Comprehend Medical DetectEntitiesV2: ~$0.01 per 100 characters (minimum 3 units). InferICD10CM: ~$0.01 per 100 characters. InferSNOMEDCT: ~$0.01 per 100 characters. A typical 3000-character note: ~$0.60 for detection + $0.05-0.20 for normalization calls per extracted problem. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Comprehend Medical** | NER extraction (DetectEntitiesV2), ICD-10 normalization (InferICD10CM), SNOMED normalization (InferSNOMEDCT) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Stores incoming clinical notes and extraction results; encrypted with KMS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Orchestrates extraction pipeline: section detection, API calls, reconciliation logic |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Stores patient problem lists with history and provenance |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Coordinates batch processing for historical note backfills |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Manages encryption keys for S3 and DynamoDB |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Logs, metrics, alarms for extraction failures and API throttling |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Reference implementations:** The following AWS sample repos demonstrate patterns used in this recipe:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m >
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-comprehend-medical-fhir-integration): End-to-end pipeline extracting clinical entities from notes and mapping to FHIR resources
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > - [`amazon-comprehend-medical-ICD10-mapping`](https://github.com/aws-samples/amazon-comprehend-medical-ICD10-mapping): ICD-10 inference from clinical text using Comprehend Medical
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m #### Walkthrough
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 1: Section detection.** Clinical notes have structure, even when they look like walls of text. Section headers ("ASSESSMENT:", "PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:", "FAMILY HISTORY:") provide critical context for assertion classification downstream. A problem mentioned under "Family History" should never end up on the patient's active problem list. This step identifies sections and tags them by category so later steps can use that context. Skip this step and you'll extract problems accurately but misclassify their assertion status, which is arguably worse than not extracting them at all.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION detect_sections(note_text):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Section header patterns found in common clinical note formats.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // These categories determine how extracted problems are interpreted downstream.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ACTIVE_SECTIONS   = ["assessment", "assessment and plan", "a/p", "active problems",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                          "problem list", "diagnoses", "impression", "current problems"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     PMH_SECTIONS      = ["past medical history", "pmh", "medical history",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                          "past history", "prior diagnoses"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FAMILY_SECTIONS   = ["family history", "fh", "family hx"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RESOLVED_SECTIONS = ["resolved problems", "inactive problems", "past problems"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ALLERGY_SECTIONS  = ["allergies", "drug allergies", "adverse reactions"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     sections = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_section = { category: "UNKNOWN", text: "", start: 0 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each line in note_text:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Check if this line is a section header.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Common patterns: "SECTION NAME:", "** Section Name **", all-caps lines.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         header = extract_header_if_present(line)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF header is not null:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Save the previous section and start a new one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF current_section.text is not empty:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 append current_section to sections
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Classify this header into a category for downstream context.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             category = classify_header(header, ACTIVE_SECTIONS, PMH_SECTIONS,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                                        FAMILY_SECTIONS, RESOLVED_SECTIONS, ALLERGY_SECTIONS)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current_section = { category: category, text: "", start: current_offset }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ELSE:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             current_section.text += line + newline
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Don't forget the last section.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     IF current_section.text is not empty:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append current_section to sections
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN sections
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 2: Extract clinical problems.** Send each relevant section to the NER service for entity extraction. We're specifically looking for entities of category MEDICAL_CONDITION, which covers diagnoses, symptoms, signs, and disease mentions. The service returns each entity with its text span, confidence score, and traits (like NEGATION or SIGN vs. DIAGNOSIS). We filter to MEDICAL_CONDITION entities and carry forward the section context from Step 1 so we know where each problem was found. Skip this step and you have no raw material for the rest of the pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION extract_problems(sections):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Process each section through the NER service.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // We only send sections that could contain relevant problem mentions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RELEVANT_CATEGORIES = ["ACTIVE", "PMH", "FAMILY", "RESOLVED", "UNKNOWN"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_problems = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each section in sections:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF section.category not in RELEVANT_CATEGORIES:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE  // skip allergy sections, medication sections, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Call the managed NER service on this section's text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         response = call ComprehendMedical.DetectEntitiesV2 with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             Text = section.text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Filter to MEDICAL_CONDITION entities only.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Other entity types (MEDICATION, ANATOMY, TEST_TREATMENT_PROCEDURE)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // are useful for other recipes but not our target here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each entity in response.Entities:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF entity.Category == "MEDICAL_CONDITION":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 problem = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     text:        entity.Text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     confidence:  entity.Score,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     begin_offset: entity.BeginOffset + section.start,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     end_offset:  entity.EndOffset + section.start,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     section:     section.category,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     traits:      entity.Traits,      // NEGATION, SIGN, DIAGNOSIS, SYMPTOM
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     attributes:  entity.Attributes   // ACUITY, DIRECTION, SYSTEM_ORGAN_SITE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 append problem to all_problems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN all_problems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 3: Classify assertion status.** This is the critical gate. Each extracted problem gets classified as active, negated, historical, family history, hypothetical, or resolved. We combine two signals: (a) the traits returned by the NER service (NEGATION trait, for example) and (b) the section context from Step 1 (a problem found in "Family History" section is family history regardless of what the NER traits say). The section context often overrides or supplements the sentence-level traits. Skip this step and your problem list fills up with negated conditions and family history items that don't belong there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION classify_assertions(problems):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Combine NER-level traits with section-level context for final assertion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     classified_problems = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each problem in problems:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Start with the section-level context as the baseline assertion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         assertion = determine_base_assertion(problem.section)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // "ACTIVE" section -> PRESENT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // "PMH" section -> HISTORICAL
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // "FAMILY" section -> FAMILY_HISTORY
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // "RESOLVED" section -> RESOLVED
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // "UNKNOWN" section -> PRESENT (default, will be refined by traits)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Now refine based on entity-level traits from the NER service.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each trait in problem.traits:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF trait.Name == "NEGATION" AND trait.Score >= 0.80:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 assertion = "NEGATED"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // Negation overrides section context. "No diabetes" in the Assessment
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // section means the patient does NOT have diabetes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF trait.Name == "HYPOTHETICAL" AND trait.Score >= 0.80:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 assertion = "HYPOTHETICAL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // "If she develops renal failure" is not an active problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Additional heuristic: check for temporal markers in surrounding text.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Words like "resolved," "s/p" (status post), "previous," "former" suggest
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // the problem is no longer active even if found in an active section.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF contains_resolution_markers(problem.text, surrounding_context):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF assertion == "PRESENT":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 assertion = "HISTORICAL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         classified_problem = problem + { assertion: assertion }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append classified_problem to classified_problems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN classified_problems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 4: Normalize to standard codes.** Active and historical problems need terminology codes for downstream use: SNOMED CT for clinical problem list maintenance, ICD-10-CM for billing and quality reporting. We call the normalization APIs with the extracted problem text and get back ranked code candidates with confidence scores. The top candidate isn't always right (especially for abbreviations or partial mentions), so we return the top 3 and let downstream consumers apply their own threshold. Skip this step and you have free-text problems that can't be reconciled, deduplicated, or used for clinical decision support.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION normalize_problems(classified_problems):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Only normalize problems that might go on the problem list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Negated and hypothetical problems don't need codes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     NORMALIZE_ASSERTIONS = ["PRESENT", "HISTORICAL", "FAMILY_HISTORY"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     normalized = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each problem in classified_problems:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF problem.assertion not in NORMALIZE_ASSERTIONS:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Still include in output for completeness, just without codes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append problem + { icd10: null, snomed: null } to normalized
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             CONTINUE
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Call ICD-10 inference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         icd10_response = call ComprehendMedical.InferICD10CM with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             Text = problem.text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Call SNOMED CT inference.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         snomed_response = call ComprehendMedical.InferSNOMEDCT with:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             Text = problem.text
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         // Take top 3 candidates from each, with scores.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         icd10_codes = top 3 concepts from icd10_response.Entities[0].ICD10CMConcepts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         snomed_codes = top 3 concepts from snomed_response.Entities[0].SNOMEDCTConcepts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         normalized_problem = problem + {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             icd10:  icd10_codes,   // [{Code, Description, Score}, ...]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             snomed: snomed_codes   // [{Code, Description, Score}, ...]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         append normalized_problem to normalized
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN normalized
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 5: Reconcile against existing problem list.** This is where extraction becomes actionable. We compare the extracted active problems against the patient's current problem list in the database. The output is a reconciliation report: new problems to consider adding, existing problems that might be resolved, and existing problems that could use specificity updates. This is always a recommendation, never an automatic update, because problem list maintenance is a clinical act that requires physician review. Skip this step and you have a nice extraction pipeline that produces results nobody acts on.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION reconcile_problems(patient_id, extracted_problems, note_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Fetch the patient's current problem list from the database.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_list = query DynamoDB for patient_id where status == "ACTIVE"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Separate extracted problems by assertion for different reconciliation logic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     active_extracted = filter extracted_problems where assertion == "PRESENT"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     resolved_signals = filter extracted_problems where assertion == "HISTORICAL"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                        OR contains_resolution_markers == true
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     recommendations = empty list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 1. Find problems mentioned as active in notes but missing from the list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each extracted in active_extracted:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF extracted.snomed[0].Code not in current_list codes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             // Potential gap: documented in note but not on problem list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to recommendations: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 type:       "ADD_CANDIDATE",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 problem:    extracted.text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 snomed:     extracted.snomed[0],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 icd10:      extracted.icd10[0],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: extracted.confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 source:     note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 rationale:  "Mentioned as active in " + extracted.section + " section"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 2. Find problems on the list that notes suggest are resolved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each existing in current_list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         IF existing.snomed_code appears in resolved_signals codes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             append to recommendations: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 type:       "RESOLVE_CANDIDATE",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 problem:    existing.problem_text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 snomed:     existing.snomed_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 confidence: resolved_signal.confidence,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 source:     note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 rationale:  "Mentioned with resolution markers in recent note"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // 3. Find specificity upgrades (e.g., "diabetes" -> "type 2 diabetes with CKD").
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each existing in current_list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         FOR each extracted in active_extracted:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             IF extracted.snomed[0].Code is_child_of existing.snomed_code:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 // More specific code found in notes than what's on the list.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 append to recommendations: {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     type:       "SPECIFICITY_UPGRADE",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     current:    existing.problem_text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     suggested:  extracted.text,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     new_snomed: extracted.snomed[0],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     new_icd10:  extracted.icd10[0],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                     source:     note_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     RETURN recommendations
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Step 6: Store results and generate reconciliation report.** Write the full extraction results to S3 for audit and reprocessing. Write reconciliation recommendations to DynamoDB where clinician review workflows can surface them. Every recommendation includes its source note, confidence score, and rationale so reviewers have enough context to accept or reject it without re-reading the entire note.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```pseudocode
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m FUNCTION store_results(patient_id, extracted_problems, recommendations, note_id):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store full extraction results in S3 for audit trail and reprocessing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     write to S3 key "results/{patient_id}/{note_id}.json":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id:          patient_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             note_id:             note_id,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             extraction_timestamp: current UTC timestamp (ISO 8601),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             problems_extracted:  extracted_problems,   // all problems with assertions and codes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             recommendations:     recommendations       // reconciliation suggestions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     // Store actionable recommendations in DynamoDB for clinician review.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     FOR each rec in recommendations:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         write to DynamoDB table "problem-list-recommendations":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             patient_id       = patient_id              // partition key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             recommendation_id = generate unique ID     // sort key
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             type             = rec.type                // ADD_CANDIDATE, RESOLVE_CANDIDATE, etc.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             problem_text     = rec.problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             snomed_code      = rec.snomed.Code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             icd10_code       = rec.icd10.Code (if present)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             confidence       = rec.confidence
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             source_note      = note_id
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             rationale        = rec.rationale
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             status           = "PENDING_REVIEW"        // awaiting clinician action
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             created_at       = current UTC timestamp
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m > **Curious how this looks in Python?** The pseudocode above covers the concepts. If you'd like to see sample Python code that demonstrates these patterns using boto3, check out the [Python Example](chapter08.05-python-example). It walks through each step with inline comments and notes on what you'd need to change for a real deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample output for a progress note mentioning several conditions:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "patient_id": "PAT-2847103",
